                    <ce:para>The capacity of a given CO
                        <inf>2</inf> capture sorbent is dependent on the operating conditions and reactor specification used during the capture and regeneration experiment, making a comparison of different sorbents difficult when evaluated under different reactor conditions. Work has been conducted comparing the capacities of many CO
                        <inf>2</inf> capture sorbents; however, due to the different mechanisms and capacities of the sorbents, each sorbent will not show its optimal performance under a standardized set of operating conditions. We propose a thermodynamic model capable of relating the capacities of sorbents under different conditions to facilitate sorbent comparisons. This model relates the capacities of a primary amine functionalized ion exchange resin under different conditions to its standard state Gibbs free energy. With an understanding of the underlying thermodynamic principles of CO
                        <inf>2</inf> interactions with amine based sorbents, one can determine the best operating conditions for each sorbent.</ce:para>
